    "## Callbacks\n",
    "\n",
    "### Callbacks as GUI events"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import ipywidgets as widgets\n",
    "\n",
    "def f(o): \n",
    "    print('hi')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "From the [ipywidget docs](https://ipywidgets.readthedocs.io/en/stable/examples/Widget%20Events.html):\n",
    "\n",
    "- *the button widget is used to handle mouse clicks. The on_click method of the Button can be used to register function to be called when the button is clicked*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "application/vnd.jupyter.widget-view+json": {
       "model_id": "1a53ea867a7b43f49d6399157fec2fbb",
       "version_major": 2,
       "version_minor": 0
      },
      "text/plain": [
       "Button(description='Click me', style=ButtonStyle())"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# create a simple widget button\n",
    "w = widgets.Button(description='Click me')\n",
    "w"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# when the button is clicked, it will call function f\n",
    "# in this sense f is a callback\n",
    "w.on_click(f)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**NB: When callbacks are used in this way they are often called \"events\".**\n",
    "\n",
    "- **events are a kind of callback**\n",
    "\n",
    "- **callback is a type of function pointer**\n",
    "\n",
    "Did you know what you can create interactive apps in Jupyter with these widgets? Here's an example from [plotly](https://plot.ly/python/widget-app/):\n",
    "\n",
    "![](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/12302455/16637308/4e476280-43ac-11e6-9fd3-ada2c9506ee1.gif)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Creating your own callback"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from time import sleep"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# lets make a simple counting function\n",
    "def slow_calculation():\n",
    "    res = 0\n",
    "    # does five calculations\n",
    "    for i in range(5):\n",
    "        res += i*i\n",
    "        sleep(1)\n",
    "    return res"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "30"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 12,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "slow_calculation()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# lets add a callback to our function\n",
    "def slow_calculation(cb=None):\n",
    "    res = 0\n",
    "    for i in range(5):\n",
    "        res += i*i\n",
    "        sleep(1)\n",
    "        if cb: cb(i)\n",
    "    return res"
   ]
  },
